history, and search or score candidate actions or short sequences against the current goal as you currently understand it.\nMaintain a compact working world model of what the current level seems to contain, what actions appear to do, what the goal seems to be, what is still uncertain, and what plan currently looks best.\nBelow you are provided with the current world model from the previous turn. The default behavior is to copy it and add or remove things based on the evidence that you gathered. BEFORE EXECUTING NEW ACTIONS YOU MUST ALWAYS GIVE THE REVISED VERSION OF THE WORLD MODEL.\nYou may call `action(actions)` more than once in one Python snippet if your search or control loop needs it, but stop immediately if a result reports `game_over`, `run_complete`, `level_completed`, or `done`.\nWorking world model carried from earlier turns:\n- World model: Level 1 has an orange background with several objects: - Top green bar (row 0, 64px) - likely HUD/timer - Charcoal block (rows 1-3, cols 36-39) and magenta block (rows 4-7, cols 36-39) stacked near top center - possibly player character - Blue rectangle (rows 16-19, cols 12-31) in middle - target or obstacle - Two yellow blocks (rows 52-59) at bottom - platforms or targets - Bottom gray bar (rows 60-63) - ground/floor\n- Goal model: Unclear yet. Need to probe what actions do.\n- Plan: Try arrow keys to see if the charcoal/magenta blocks move (player character). Then try SPACE.\n- Revise any item above immediately if `current_frame` or `history` contradicts it.\nend of world model. \nFocus on what changed most recently in `history`, update the target environment change if needed, and separate gameplay-object changes from HUD-only changes.\nWhen ready, call `action(actions)` from inside the `python` tool with the best valid action or ordered batch selected by your code. If your code has found a reliable short sequence, prefer batching it in one call.\nYou may call `action(actions)` more than once in one Python snippet if your search or control loop needs it.\nIf you include assistant text before a tool call, keep it short and use it to update the world model. Helpful optional prefixes are `World model:`, `Goal model:`, `Action model:`, `Recent findings:`, `Open questions:`, `Plan:`, and `Cross-level notes:`.\nWhen calling `python`, emit exactly the tool-call format shown elsewhere in this prompt for this model. Use only that format; do not add markdown fences, prose wrappers, or alternate tool-call syntax. Do not quote or place tool-call markup inside explanatory text; when you decide to call the tool, emit the tool call itself.\nIf you use MOUSE, include integer row and col arguments.\nEFFICIENCY BUDGET \u2014 your score on each level is (baseline_actions / your_actions)^2, so every wasted action costs you quadratically.\nLevel 1: you have used 1 of about 39 target actions so far.", "kind": "tool", "inContext": true}, {"label": "THINKING", "content": "The board changed after pressing RIGHT. Let me check what moved by comparing the before and after frames.", "kind": "reasoning", "inContext": false}, {"label": "TOOL CALL: python", "content": "<tool_call>\n<function=python>\n<parameter=code>\n# Compare before and after RIGHT press\nbefore = last_transition.before_frame.segmentation['nodes']\nafter = current_frame.segmentation['nodes']\n\nprint(\"BEFORE -> AFTER comparison:\")\nfor bn, an in zip(before, after):\n    b_rows = [p[0] for p in bn['boundary']]\n    b_cols = [p[1] for p in bn['boundary']]\n    a_rows = [p[0] for p in an['boundary']]\n    a_cols = [p[1] for p in an['boundary']]\n    changed = (min(b_rows)!=min(a_rows) or min(b_cols)!=min(a_cols))\n    if changed:\n        print(f\"  Node {bn['id']} ({bn['color']}): rows {min(b_rows)}-{max(b_rows)}->{min(a_rows)}-{max(a_rows)}, cols {min(b_cols)}-{max(b_cols)}->{min(a_cols)}-{max(a_cols)}\")\n</parameter>\n</function>\n</tool_call>", "kind": "tool", "inContext": true}, {"label": "TOOL RESULT: python", "content": "BEFORE -> AFTER comparison:\n  Node 1 (O): rows 1-59->0-0, cols 0-63->62-63\n  Node 2 (c): rows 1-3->1-59, cols 36-39->0-63\n  Node 3 (M): rows 4-7->1-3, cols 36-39->36-39\n  Node 4 (b): rows 16-19->4-7, cols 12-31->36-39\n  Node 5 (Y): rows 52-59->16-19, cols 16-27->16-35\n  Node 6 (Y): rows 52-59->52-59, cols 40-51->16-27\n  Node 7 (w): rows 60-63->52-59, cols 0-63->40-51", "kind": "tool", "inContext": true}, {"label": "THINKING", "content": "The node IDs shifted but the objects themselves seem to have changed positions. Let me re-examine by color instead of by ID, since IDs are assigned by top-left ordering.", "kind": "reasoning", "inContext": false}, {"label": "TOOL CALL: python", "content": "<tool_call>\n<function=python>\n<parameter=code>\n# Compare by color since IDs shift with ordering\ndef get_by_color(nodes, color):\n    for n in nodes:\n        if n['color'] == color:\n            rows = [p[0] for p in n['boundary']]\n            cols = [p[1] for p in n['boundary']]\n            return (min(rows), max(rows), min(cols), max(cols), n['pixels'])\n    return None\n\nbefore = last_transition.before_frame.segmentation['nodes']\nafter = current_frame.segmentation['nodes']\n\ncolors = ['N', 'O', 'c', 'M', 'b', 'Y', 'w']\nfor color in colors:\n    b = get_by_color(before, color)\n    a = get_by_color(after, color)\n    if b and a:\n        changed = b != a\n        if changed:\n            print(f\"  {color}: {b} -> {a}\")\n        else:\n            print(f\"  {color}: unchanged {b}\")\n</parameter>\n</function>\n</tool_call>", "kind": "tool", "inContext": true}, {"label": "TOOL RESULT: python", "content": "N: (0, 0, 0, 63, 64) -> (0, 0, 0, 61, 62)\n  O: unchanged (1, 59, 0, 63, 3508)\n  c: unchanged (1, 3, 36, 39, 12)\n  M: unchanged (4, 7, 36, 39, 16)\n  b: (16, 19, 12, 31, 80) -> (16, 19, 16, 35, 80)\n  Y: unchanged (52, 59, 16, 27, 80)\n  w: unchanged (60, 63, 0, 63, 256)", "kind": "tool", "inContext": true}, {"label": "THINKING", "content": "Interesting! After pressing